liest known non-sanskrit translation of the Gita) - considered, (with dif=\r\nfering nuances on the relation between jiva, paramatma, moksha etc), Krshna=\r\n as the ultimate conception of God on earth. This was aided in no less a me=\r\nasure by the delcaration of the earliest Puranas, that is Vishnu Purana and=\r\n the SB, that Krshna was a complete Avatara. Some, like the Gaudiya Vaishna=\r\nvas, went one step ahead and took a very literal view of it all and declare=\r\nd Krshna as the Ultimate Being, and the formless Paramatma, as well as Nara=\r\nyana, as merely the aura of Krshna. Rama was also intricately linked to thi=\r\ns Krshnaa-ism, but was looked at as the earlier brith of Krshna, not as a s=\r\neparate Divity in himself.\n \nWhatever the case maybe, each school had its o=\r\nwn set of established saints and scholars to vouch for their views. So it b=\r\noiled down to interpretation, which is often, as you rightly pointed out, b=\r\nased on various conditionings.\n \nWe human beings are creatures of imaginati=\r\non. Whenever an Avatar appears on the earth, most of the great Mahatmas who=\r\n appear after the Avatara, remain overawed by the character of the last Ava=\r\ntara because invariable in the context of the desh-kaal-patra of those time=\r\ns, the life of the Avatara shows actions performed which are way beyond ima=\r\ngination for *those times*. Such a situation continues until the next Avata=\r\nra comes on earth. I am sure in the period after Rama, and before Krshna, o=\r\nf which we have very little written record, the world at large remained ent=\r\nirely overawed by Rama Avatara.\n \nIn this light Krshna is the Poorna-Avatar=\r\na. When Kalki will appear on earth, he will be invarible accompanied by a s=\r\net of powerful Rishis - every Avatara comes with his coterie of Rishis who =\r\nexplain the philosophy and spirituality of the Avatara to the general masse=\r\ns - who will then create new scriptures and Kalki will be looked at as the =\r\ncrest jewel of the Avataras.\n \n*  *   *\n \nI believe in the evolutionary par=\r\nable of these 9 Avatara because I find no other reason why these set of Ava=\r\ntara, from the whole list of possible Avataras, have captured the popular i=\r\nmagination. I mean Dattatreya is an Avatara too as per SB. His spirituality=\r\n is no less than that of any other Avatara. Yet, he is not in the list of 9=\r\n/10 Avataras. \n \nThe original Nath Yogis used to consider Nine Chakras in t=\r\nhe Human Body. The idea of Kundalini Yoga also came from them, which was ba=\r\nsically exploring cronologically all these nine chakras one after the other=\r\n by flooding them with Chit-Shakti.\n \nThere are 9 basic grahas in jyotish. =\r\nEach graha could very well represent the essential nature of each chakra. A=\r\nll these make me more sanguine that there must be Nine Evolutionary Avatara=\r\ns, not ten. In which case Kalki must be the Ninth Avatara.\n \nBuddha, as you=\r\n rightly pointed out, has a tremendous logical appeal in Kali Yuga. But if =\r\nlogic is the criteria, then why not Adi Shankara? I may not agree to his ph=\r\nilosophy as it comes down to us from his followers, but it cannot be denied=\r\n that Adi Shankara was arguable one of the sharpest and most logical of spi=\r\nritual philosphers. His intellectual and logical mind is beyond doubt. Just=\r\n that Shankara never claimed himself to be an Avatara. Neither did Siddhart=\r\nha. Only that the later came 3000 years ago, and the former came possibly i=\r\nn the last 1000 years. Shankara&#39;s spiritual impact on the world is no less =\r\nthan that of the Buddha. What mainstream Hinduism today is, could not have =\r\nbeen, had it not been for the invaluable contribution of Adi Shankara. And =\r\nif Buddha was truly the awaited 9th Avatara of Vishnu, Shankara would not h=\r\nave been able to absorb the philosophy of Buddha into Hinduism and thus mak=\r\ne it lose its grip on India. Buddhism barely exists in land of its birth.\n =\r\n\nAll this taken together, make me more and more convinced that there are 9 =\r\nevolutionary Avataras and the 9th is yet to come.\n \n*  *  *\n \nA little bit =\r\nabout Rama and Krshna. When I said I admire Rama, it is not a lip-service. =\r\nThere are incidents in the Ramayana which I find extremely inspiring, educa=\r\ntive and uplifting. Like the incident where Rama was to cross the ocean. Ra=\r\nma knew very well that if he wanted, in one moment he could have used his D=\r\nivine Astras and forced the ocean to yield way to his army. Yet he sat in s=\r\nilent supplication for days, praying that the ocean allow his army safe pas=\r\nsage. When all else failed, when genuine goodwill was not recirpocated, and=\r\n it was absolutely necessary to cross the ocean, THEN Rama took up weapons =\r\nto get the job done. A powerful warrior, who knows very well how powerful h=\r\ne himself is, not letting that sense of power pervert his mind even for a m=\r\noment is an amazing phenomenon. This kind of self-control is rare and worth=\r\ny of comtemplation, specially by anyone who feels, ever so slightly, that h=\r\ne/she has some form of power or influence in this world in any sphere. Rama=\r\n had no malice for anyone. Not even Ravana, by the end of the war at least.=\r\n He was the very personification of Satwa. In Satwa, conflict and malice an=\r\nd cunningness are impossible.\n \nRecently, a friend of mine told me that he =\r\nhas learnt all his life that one must listen to Krshna&#39;s advice, but only f=\r\nollow what Rama did, and not what Krshna did. I disagree with this vehement=\r\nly. If one reads entire Krshna&#39;s life with an objective mind, Krshna of Vrn=\r\ndavana, Krshna of Mathura, Krshna of Kurushetra, Krshna the Jagat Guru who =\r\nspeaks the Gita, one will find that what Krshna the Guru adviced in the Git=\r\na, Krshna the Divine Worker himself followed it all through his life at eve=\r\nry instance. It is his perfect detachment under all circumstances of life, =\r\nfrom childhood to his death, that makes me wonder, was this a man or was th=\r\nis a God? Can a man even do something like this? It is as if there is a par=\r\nt of Krshna who is always separate from everything, and silently watches th=\r\ne whole scene with a bemused smile. He had not a single personal stake in t=\r\nhe Mahabharata. Rama at least had his wife abducted for him to start a war =\r\nagainst Ravana. But Krshna had zero personal stake in the Mahabharata. Afte=\r\nr liberating his parents from Kamsa, very soon he went off to meet the Pand=\r\navas. From out of nowhere he forced himself into the politics of the Mahabh=\r\narata, and precipitated a great war to cleanse the world of burden. While L=\r\nakshmana devoutly followed Rama all along the Ramayana and they were like a=\r\nn inseparable pair, as Balarama in his next incarnation he could hardly und=\r\nerstand Krshna. There are so many occassions where Balarama asks Krshna, wh=\r\nat are they doing with all these kings, and that they should return to thei=\r\nr village in Vrndavana. Krshna merely smiles. He knows that not everyone wi=\r\nll understand everything. But that cannot stop him from following his dharm=\r\na, with perfect detachement from eveyrthing of this plane. Neither false pr=\r\naises, nor wrong accusations by his close people can affect him one bit. An=\r\nd I am not even counting the miracles he perfromed as a Divine Child. So I =\r\nworship Krshna, because I have not yet met or heard of read of a single sad=\r\nhaka or saint or ordinary man or mahatma who has displayed this kind of per=\r\nfected detachment through thick and thin, yet not withdrawing from the worl=\r\nd or actively performing a larger dharma.\n \nI started appreciating Swami Vi=\r\nvekanada more after I understood a bit of the Krshna Avatara. That was the =\r\nlast known saint who lived a whirlwind life in the middle of a circus-stopl=\r\night of fame and accusations, on one side adoring admirers and on the other=\r\n bitter enemies accusing him of being a heretic right upto the very end of =\r\nhis brief life, and yet none of that affected him to any great degree. He f=\r\naced terrific racism in the America, yet not a single speech of his reflect=\r\ns the slightest trace of bitterness, anger, or negativity. That is such a f=\r\nantastic achievement, IMHO.\n \nI agree with you, Narasimha, for most of us i=\r\nt is better to try to mould ones life with the same kind of supreme selfles=\r\nsness that Rama showed all along. Not just worship Rama but more importantl=\r\ny study his life and imbibe, to whatever degree possible, the quality he re=\r\npresented. Maybe, just maybe, then the Unmanifested Reality - Shiva - will =\r\nfix the mind so firmly on that Reality, that in some future life, in some l=\r\nater birth, one will be able to live life like Krshna showed, unattached an=\r\nd unaffected by any dirt that the world throws up. And then the Universal C=\r\nhit-Shakti (Adya Shakti) will flood such an individual with oppulence unima=\r\nginable, of this world and also of what lies in other worlds, like Krshna&#39;s=\r\n six oppulences - Infinite wealth, infinite beauty, infinite power/knowledg=\r\ne, infinite fame, and infinite detachment from all the other five. \n \n \nEnj=\r\noyed this discussion. :)\n \nJai Jai Rama Krshna Hari!\n \n-Regards\n Rajarshi\n =\r\n\nawaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah | param bhAwamajAnanto mamAw=\r\nyayamanuttamam ||[7:24]\n\nFrom: Narasimha P.V.R. Rao &lt;pvr108@...&gt;\nTo: =\r\n&quot;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&quot; &lt;vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com&gt;\nSent: Sunday,=\r\n 5 May 2013 10:59 PM\nSubject: [vedic-wisdom] Re: Comparing Dasavataras!\n\n  =\r\n\nDear Rajarshi,\n \nEven Parasara did not say there are just 9 or 10 avataras=\r\n or that there is a one-to-one correspondence to grahas. He too said there =\r\nare innumerable avataras. Avataras can come with a combination of paramatma=\r\nmsas (supreme/absolute being portions) and jivatmamsas (living/relative bei=\r\nng portions) taken from grahas in any combination. Though 9 main avataras o=\r\nf Vishnu came from paramatmamsas of 9 grahas, many many other avataras also=\r\n descended on earth due to various other combinations of paramatmamsas and =\r\njivatmamsas of the same 9 grahas! There are obviously many possibilities.\n =\r\n\nIn fact, Parasara says that ALL beings contain some paramatmamsa and some =\r\njivatmamsa, coming from grahas. But jivatmamsa is predominant in most of us=\r\n.\n \nWhen one leaves earth, paramatmamsas in one return to respective grahas=\r\n and jivatmamsas take birth again based on desires. In the &#39;end&#39;, even the =\r\njivatmamsas return to respective grahas. At the time of Mahapralaya, grahas=\r\n also merge back in Supreme Lord.\n \n*        *        *\n \nAs for Kalki, Par=\r\nasara did not clarify and we can only speculate. Though some people associa=\r\nte him with lagna, that makes no sense to me either. That is inconsistent w=\r\nith the overall framework laid by Parasara (i.e. beings born with combinati=\r\nons of paramatmamsas and jivatmamsas from *grahas*).\n \nKalki will probably =\r\ncome with paramatmamsas of both Sun and Moon. After all, Kalki shows Shiva =\r\nand Shakti (Sun and Moon - soul and mind) coming together finally!! Just a =\r\nspeculation..\n \n*        *        *\n \nWhether you take 9 or 10 or 22 avatar=\r\nas, the theory of evolutionary spiritual perfection does not add up because=\r\n &quot;perfection&quot; occurred before the last avatara, unless you break away from =\r\nmain scriptures and throw away Buddha (and discount Kalki as he has not com=\r\ne yet).\n \n*        *        *\n \nRather than &quot;evolution&quot;, it is a matter of =\r\nwhat the world needs at that time. If people at the beginning of Satya yuga=\r\n are established in Self always and the only issue is that a small attachme=\r\nnt may develop now and then, disturbing that state of being established in =\r\nSelf (i.e. stealing of Veda!), then the aspect of consciousness that is rel=\r\nevant is &quot;spirit of detachment&quot; (Ketu). If invoked, it removes that attachm=\r\nent and takes one back to being established in Self. So an avatara correspo=\r\nnding to Ketu occurred.\n \nAs collective consciousness became denser, being =\r\nestablished in Self became less natural and more effort was needed. So the =\r\n&quot;spirit of patience, persistence and hard-work&quot; (Saturn) became relevant an=\r\nd an avatara corresponding to Saturn occurred. And so on.\n \nIn the dark age=\r\ns of Kali yuga, rational minds wouldn&#39;t accept anything that didn&#39;t &quot;make s=\r\nense&quot;. Being established in Self became an unnatural, ridiculous and incomp=\r\nrehensible notion. So the &quot;spirit of comprehension&quot; (Mercury) became releva=\r\nnt. An avatara corresponding to Mercury occurred and tried to explain being=\r\n established in Self as a comprehensible notion, so that rational minds of =\r\nthat age would accept it to an extent and attempt it.\n \nAvataras occur base=\r\nd on the needs of collective consciousness. Of course, if one&#39;s consciousne=\r\nss is in a different state from the collective consciousness of that time, =\r\nthe current avatara may not be relevant to one.\n \n*        *        *\n \n&gt; I=\r\n respect Rama, but I worship Krshna.\n \nI am awestruck by Krishna and worshi=\r\np him, but I see Rama as an ideal that I MAY be able to emulate oneday. In =\r\nfact, I recommend the approach to others.\n \nThough I said Rama and Krishna =\r\nare almost the same, there is a difference between soul and perfected mind.=\r\n Soul is a spark of Shiva and a perfected mind is a spark of Chit Shakti (w=\r\nhereas an imperfect mind is a spark of Maya shakti).\n \n\nBest regards,Narasi=\r\nmha--------Astrology & Spirituality Resources: http://www.vedicastrologer.o=\r\nrg/\n--------\n \n\n\tFrom: rajarshi nandy &