think of him. And then righ=\r\nt in the middle of the greatest war he had the perfect equipoise to deliver=\r\n the most sublime spiritual philosophy. That is why his life remains the be=\r\nst ideal of Karma-Yoga. For a true Karma-Yogi by definition can never be de=\r\njected. It is impossible. Neither the action nor the results belong to the =\r\ninstrument. When running away from the battle-field and killing Kaliya Yava=\r\nna, or when advising Bheema to tear apart Jarashanda, or gesturing Bheema t=\r\no hit Duryodhana below the waist, or getting Shikhandi to face Bhisma, Krsh=\r\nna, as if by some Divine Intuition, knew exactly how the situations must be=\r\n lined up which would cause the destruction of these people. This kind of k=\r\nnowledge cannot come by the rational thinking. But happens when one is cons=\r\ntantly and consciously connected to the Universal Force. We do not find the=\r\nse kind of complex situations in the Rama Avatara, at least in the Valmiki =\r\nRamayana. Of course, if we take the Adhbut Ramayana or such other auxilliar=\r\ny texts and retelling, we get a different picture. In the Adbhuta Ramayana =\r\nwe have a 1000 headed demon attacking Rama after he kills Ravana, and then =\r\nSita turns into Adya Shakti and demolishes the 1000 headed demon and Rama w=\r\norships her. But if we take only the Ramayana and the Mahabharata, the pict=\r\nure that emerges is very clear. Rama is the embodiment of Sattwic mind. The=\r\nrefore he displays all the great characteristics of satwa, chief of which i=\r\ns self-control, as well as the occasional sadness caused due to separation =\r\nfrom his wife Sita whom, at least until Ravana was destroyed, he loved very=\r\n dearly. Satwa guna creates a true saint, but can also cause some grief whe=\r\nn the stability is shaken. Krshna was gunatita. He had no attachment to any=\r\nthing in this world - man, women, deva, danava, friend, enemy - and therefo=\r\nre he was never affected any trace of negative emotion. His Ananda never le=\r\nft him even in the most trying situations. 6. Buddha was great spiritual fo=\r\nrce in this world. But I do not see him fit in the scheme of evolutionary A=\r\nvatars. His realization, the one he advocated, is a static realization, an =\r\nend in a void. This is clearly denying of the reality of this earth. I find=\r\n this not in tune with what either Rama or Krshna espoused. None of them ne=\r\ngated this world. If negation of this world and life is the final aim, then=\r\n why send so many avatars at crucial stages of evolutionary development? If=\r\n the spiritual impact on masses is the reason for Buddha being an Avatara, =\r\nthen why not Jesus or Zorathrusta.? They are no less impactful in that sens=\r\ne. But do they fit in the scheme of spiritual line that these 9 Avataras of=\r\n Narayana indicate in a most logical manner? No. As such many vaishnava tra=\r\nditions in parts of India, do not consider Buddha to be an avatara. Realiza=\r\ntion, to be complete and holistic, must be both static and dynamic, outside=\r\n of life as well as inside of life. That is why the Tantras formed their ow=\r\nn kind of spiritual philosophy, of the world as body of Shakti and therefor=\r\ne an object of reverence and realization. 7. The original literature of the=\r\n Nath Yogis used to mention 9 chakras. These are centers of psychological f=\r\nunctions. 6 inside the human body and 3 too subtle, or non-developed in mos=\r\nt people, even seekers. It is my belief that each of the 9 Avataras - exclu=\r\nding Buddha - correspond to the full power and force of one of these 9 Chak=\r\nras. Similarly, the 9 grahas, or that which can modify consciousness or all=\r\now the consciousness to explore and express itself is various possiblities,=\r\n are 9 in number. The lagna is a reference point and not a graha. Therefore=\r\n the chief Avatars who represent the parable of evolution are nine in numbe=\r\nr. And the ninth of the sequence is yet to come.