he Cosmos.   *        *        *   One who is fasc=\r\ninated by the qualities of soul may like the story that demonstrates how so=\r\nul operates; one who is fascinated by the qualities of mind may like the st=\r\nory that demonstrates how mind operates, and one who is fascinated by the q=\r\nualities of wisdom may like the story that demonstrates how wisdom operates=\r\n. And so on. But this is just a matter of taste and subjective preference. =\r\n  *        *        *   Let us focus on Rama and Krishna, i.e. soul and min=\r\nd. Soul is seen as a representative of god in us, because of some basic att=\r\nributes of it. It is the higher self and has no agendas, no likes or dislik=\r\nes.   Once mind fancies a separate existence with some agendas/desires, sou=\r\nl supports the individualized consciousness stemming from that fancy and se=\r\nes it as its dharma. It lends strength and support to EVERY aspect of this =\r\nindividualized consciousness (e.g. mind, energy, intellect, learning abilit=\r\ny, enjoyment, discipline etc). It supports them fully and yet has no desire=\r\ns/agendas/likes/dislikes of its own! It impassionately witnesses and record=\r\ns all of one&#39;s agendas and karmas so that Laws of Nature give proper fruits=\r\n later on. It does all that despite full awareness that it is neither doing=\r\n those karmas nor receiving the fruits. As mind and other aspects of the in=\r\ndividualized consciousness entertain the notion that they are doing things =\r\nand begetting the fruits, soul supports them fully in this play. It sees th=\r\nat as its dharma and does it impassionately.   Now, does this sound excitin=\r\ng? Perhaps not to all. This functionality of an impassionate witness suppor=\r\nting the play, may not seem interesting enough to some.   On the other hand=\r\n, mind has likes, dislikes and agendas. It is constantly pursuing those age=\r\nndas, getting things and achieving things. Movement of mind is what keeps t=\r\nhe individualization going!!! Though soul is the support for everything els=\r\ne in the individualized consciousness, soul is a witness doing its dharma i=\r\nmpassionately. It is mind that keeps the individualization going and brings=\r\n in agendas and passion and even decides/affects every entity&#39;s dharma. Tha=\r\nt way, mind is really the &quot;boss&quot; of the individualization. No wonder Krishn=\r\na&#39;s life appeals more to one who may be excited by this description!   *   =\r\n     *        *   Lord Krishna is obviously awe-inspiring, but let me put R=\r\nama&#39;s life in perspective.   Rama&#39;s life demonstrates how soul operates. At=\r\n a young age, he received Brahma Jnana from Vasishtha and became realized. =\r\nYet, he did whatever was his &quot;dharma&quot;. He helped Vishwamitra. Soon after ma=\r\nrriage, he was given kingdom. At the last moment, his father banished him t=\r\no forest at the behest of his step-mother and his step-brother was given th=\r\ne throne. He had no complaints. Though his father, step-mother and step-bro=\r\nther felt guilty to various degrees, he himself supported and consoled all =\r\nthree and followed his dharma impassionately. Though he knew leaving Sita i=\r\nn the forest with Lakshmana and going after the golden deer would cause pro=\r\nblems, he did it impassionately when Sita insisted. When she was kidnapped =\r\nby Ravana, he searched for her and fought the battle. He never faulted Sita=\r\n for forcing him to leave her or faulted Lakshmana for leaving her later. H=\r\ne accepted every life situation with no complaints and did the best possibl=\r\ne action then. Even as he killed Ravana, he did so without hatred or anger,=\r\n but as his impassionate dharma. Even as Ravana was dying, he went to him a=\r\nnd respectfully learned some subjects that were going to disappear with Rav=\r\nana!   Rama is a perfect example of a liberated man with no desires or agen=\r\ndas who impassionately discharges one&#39;s dharma arising from the momentum of=\r\n karmas before liberation. THAT is basically what soul does!   *        *  =\r\n      *   As another example, let us look at Lord Vaamana. His story is a p=\r\nerfect demonstration of how wisdom/discrimination operates.   He was born a=\r\ns a learned pygmy. He filled the entire cosmos to rid earth of a charitable=\r\n demon king with many great qualities.   Wisdom/discrimination makes one hu=\r\nmble and unassuming. When one is doing good work but tainted with demonic q=\r\nualities (e.g. pride or attachment), one&#39;s discrimination is not pleased un=\r\ntil that pride is suppressed. When wisdom fills one&#39;s entire consciousness,=\r\n then demonic qualities are completely suppressed.   *        *        *   =\r\nPlease think about the other avataras. The stories can be understood as per=\r\nfect demonstrations of how various aspects of our consciousness operate, ba=\r\nsed on clues from Maharshi Parasara.   Let us not compare Dasavataras, but =\r\ncelebrate each of them separately. Of course, if you are more attracted to =\r\none of them, please think about that avatara more and develop devotion. The=\r\ny are ALL capable of relieving us from samsara.   *        *        *   By =\r\nthe way, happy Hanumajjayanti to those who celebrate it today (there are di=\r\nfferent schools of thought).   Best regards, Narasimha -------- Astrology &=\r\n Spirituality Resources: http://www.VedicAstrologer.org -------- \n\n\t\n\n\n\n\n"}}